etymologies: mid 19th century; earliest use found in Secret Songs Silence. Origin unknown

definitions: A young saithe or coalfish, Pollachius virens.

etymologies: early 18th century; earliest use found in John Kelly (c1684–1751), writer. Probably a variant of prickle with infixed -n-; compare later pringle

definitions: To have or cause a pricking sensation, like the feeling of ‘pins and needles’; to prickle, tingle.
To twinkle, sparkle. Chiefly Scottish and English regional.
